<h3>PHP &amp; MySQL Class Server<br />
</h3>
<table style="width: 100%; text-align: left;" border="0" cellpadding="2"
 cellspacing="2">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; text-align: right; width: 25%;"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Host &amp; Domain Name:</span><br />
      </td>
      <td style="border-bottom: 1px solid black; vertical-align: top;">&nbsp;
itins3.matcmadison.edu<br />
      </td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<ol>
  <li><span style="font-weight: bold;">About our class server:</span> <br />
    <br />
Each student will have an account on a shared Linux-based server.
You may use it to store copies of PHP files for in-class labs and projects.
We will use it for some labs during the semester.
Student usernames on the server will be first initial and last
name. The instructor will tell you the password at the first class period.<br />
    <br />
  </li>
  <li><span style="font-weight: bold;">Sign-On instructions:</span><br />
<p>To sign-on to the server, use <b>ssh</b> from your Linux virtual machine (VM):</p>
<blockquote><code>
ssh djefferson@itins3.matcmadison.edu<br>
</code></blockquote>
<p>From a Windows PC you can use the <b>Putty</b> terminal emulator to connect
to the class server.</p>
<p>Only use YOUR first initial and last name. You will be prompted for a password.
Once you login to the server you may change your password using the <b>passwd</b>
command.</p>
</li>
  <li><span style="font-weight: bold;">Copying Files:</span><br />
    <p class="WW-BodyTextIndent2"
 style="margin-left: 0in; text-indent: 0in;">Use the
secure copy command, <b>scp</b>, to copy the files to and from the
server from your Linux VM. To copy to a directory on the server use:</p>
<blockquote><code>
scp filename djefferson@itins3.matcmadison.edu:/home/djefferson/<br>
</code></blockquote>
<p>To copy from a directory on the server to your current directory use:</p>
<blockquote><code>
scp djefferson@itins3.matcmadison.edu:/home/djefferson/filename .<br>
</code></blockquote>
<p>
Note the period (.) at the end of the last command! It indicates that the file
should be copied to the current directory and given the same name as the source file.
</p>
<p>On Windows you can download and install <b>WinSCP</b> to copy files to and from
the class server.</p>
</li>
</ol>
